webcam_probe.py is the live Phase 0 check, and landmark_normalization.py is the math/helper layer it relies on.
What webcam_probe.py does
Opens your webcam with OpenCV.
Loads a MediaPipe Face Landmarker model from --model-path.
Detects one face per frame.
Extracts the 478 landmarks into a [[x, y, z], ...] array.
Passes that array into normalize_landmarks(...).
Displays the live video with a small overlay showing:scale
the mean of the normalized landmark array

Lets you quit with q.
See: [`phase0/webcam_probe.py`](C:/dev/real-time-3D-avatar-s-facial-animation/phase0/webcam_probe.py)
What landmark_normalization.py does
Defines the normalization rule for landmarks.
Centers the face on a stable anchor computed from landmark indices (1, 6, 168).
Computes scale from the distance between landmarks (33, 263), which acts like an eye-width reference.
Normalizes all landmarks by subtracting the anchor and dividing by that scale.
Converts a dataset row with x_0/y_0/z_0 ... columns into a (n, 3) landmark array.
Provides a small drift summary for sanity checks:scale
centroid magnitude after normalization
average spread

See: [`phase0/landmark_normalization.py`](C:/dev/real-time-3D-avatar-s-facial-animation/phase0/landmark_normalization.py)
In plain English
webcam_probe.py answers: “Can we see a face from the webcam, run MediaPipe, and produce normalized landmarks live?”
landmark_normalization.py answers: “How do we make those landmarks position- and scale-invariant so head movement matters less?”
If you want, I can also explain the exact anchor points and why those landmark indices were chosen.
